<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What are Open Graph tags?", answer: "Open Graph (OG) tags are HTML meta tags that control how a URL is displayed when shared on social media platforms like Facebook, LinkedIn, and others. They were introduced by Facebook in 2010 and have become the standard for social sharing metadata. The four required OG tags are og:title (the title of the page), og:type (the type of content, usually 'website' or 'article'), og:image (the URL of the preview image), and og:url (the canonical URL). Additional tags like og:description and og:site_name provide further context." },
  { question: "Why are Open Graph tags important?", answer: "Without OG tags, social media platforms guess what title, description, and image to use when someone shares your URL. This often results in incorrect or missing information, cropped images, or generic text that does not encourage clicks. Properly configured OG tags give you full control over your social media appearance, leading to higher click-through rates, more engagement, and a professional appearance when your content is shared. They are essential for content marketing, brand consistency, and social SEO." },
  { question: "What is the twitter:card meta tag?", answer: "The twitter:card meta tag tells Twitter how to display your content when shared. There are two main card types: 'summary' shows a small square image with title and description, while 'summary_large_image' shows a large rectangular image above the title and description. Twitter also supports OG tags as fallbacks, so if twitter:title is not set, Twitter will use og:title instead. Setting the card type is the minimum required Twitter-specific tag; all other Twitter tags can fall back to their OG equivalents." },
  { question: "What image size should I use for Open Graph?", answer: "Facebook recommends images of at least 1200 x 630 pixels for optimal display on high-resolution devices. The minimum recommended size is 600 x 315 pixels. Images smaller than 200 x 200 pixels may not be displayed. For Twitter summary_large_image cards, the recommended size is 1200 x 628 pixels with a 2:1 aspect ratio. For summary cards, use a square image of at least 144 x 144 pixels. Keep file size under 5 MB for Facebook and 5 MB for Twitter. Use JPEG, PNG, GIF, or WebP formats." },
  { question: "How do I debug Open Graph tags?", answer: "Facebook provides the Sharing Debugger tool (developers.facebook.com/tools/debug) that shows exactly how Facebook parses your OG tags and what the preview will look like. It also lets you scrape the URL again to refresh Facebook's cache. Twitter provides the Card Validator (cards-dev.twitter.com/validator) for testing Twitter Card markup. LinkedIn has its Post Inspector tool (linkedin.com/post-inspector). Always test your OG tags with these tools before launching a marketing campaign to ensure the previews look correct across all platforms." }
]) %>

